The (also overwhelmingly white!) EDS researcher community hasn't been accountable for the ways in which patient knowledge is collected and used and the very real (and racially uneven!) impacts on EDSers' lives and wellbeing.

The overwhelmingly white EDS patient community hasn't reckoned with the ways that white supremacy shapes research on the condition, patient experiences, access to diagnosis and care, advocacy opportunities, peer interactions, and much more.

All of these things are true and can come into conflict. These patterns structure our interactions. The specific instance to which a person responds is rarely the first time that they've encountered it, so engaging in good faith does not preclude conflict.

These patterns are: the persistent marginalization of scholars of colour, the whiteness of the EDS patient community, and the instrumentalization of patient knowledge and gatekeeping of expertise by researchers.

It has also been easier to make new, geographically distant friends. I have connected with so many people in the past two years who I never would have gotten to know in the "before times". My social circle is wider and my social life busier than it has ever been.

We've had to find, strengthen, and/or acclimate to alternative modes of connection. As a result, it has been easier to keep in touch with far-away friends, chronically ill and disabled friends, and friends with complicated demands on their time and energy.

Obviously one of the hardest things about the pandemic is how it has impacted familiar forms of intimacy and care, but I want to call attention for a moment to the ways in which it has also opened up entirely new geographies of intimacy and care.

And here I am including an image of a passage about the history of attributing particular traits to coat colouration (it should give you all of the racialized, gendered, classed, and colonial/imperial heebie-jeebies): https://t.co/m6AMpoZ8uM
Or should we be more thoughtful about how our expectations of and therefore interactions with various animals shape how those animals behave and the relationships we have with them?

Today we take for granted that "breeds" exist and that a cat's colouration can tell us things about that cat (e.g. that tortie cats are smart and sassy, that orange male cats are sweet and "slow", etc...) -- but should we?

"Racializing" domestic animals, the formalization of "breeds", and the practice of associating various attributes to coat colouration actually did play a critical role in the emergence of scientific racism during the 1800s.
Lastly, Pam is actually on to something in being troubled by cat coat colouration being tied to personality and behaviours.

And here's where I want us to think carefully about how the ways that both Pam and Jorts are being portrayed in this story is also shoring up dominant beliefs about disability and worth (Jorts as a "stupid" cat and Pam as a "crazy" woman).

Furthermore, we are likely to make certain assumptions about Pam based on our gendered associations. Pam is slotted into the "crazy" cat lady archetype, and her presumed detachment from reality/"appropriate" interspecies behaviours adds another level of supposed humour.

But underneath it all are, in fact, conflicting assumptions about what two beings require in order live their best feline lives -- and, by extension, differing understandings of the interspecies responsibilities of Jean and Jorts's human co-workers.

...of workplace etiquette, Pam's earnest investment in Jorts's dignity and wellbeing, the OP's tone and delivery, and the exercise of determining who is "the asshole" versus cats' inherent "silliness". (As readers, we understand even the phrase "Jorts's wellbeing" as ridiculous.)

And to me that's why dad jokes provide a revolutionary sort of masculinity hidden in plain sight -- so mundane and expected that you've probably rolled your eyes at it a hundred times without noticing why it's actually so special.

It's a masculinity that actually invites others to laugh at OR with it (as they choose).

It's an example of a joyful masculinity with no shame, cynicism, or violence.
It's an example of generous, nurturing, playful, interactive, nonhierarchical masculinity.

Rather, it invites the listener to play along (either as a "hey have you heard this one..." fellow dad or as a "ugh you're so embarrassing" straight man).

That's the anatomy -- and the genius -- of a dad joke.
So dad jokes are simultaneously self-deprecating humour that is not self-critical AND an extremely low-stakes kind of teasing that doesn't direct any negativity towards the other person.
The tension that makes a dad joke funny (bc humour relies on tension) is in the social awkwardness of the performance -- it's in the "dad's" enjoyment of the joke and not its content.

They are told bc the "dad" wants to laugh at himself and bc he's trying to gently provoke an interaction/reaction (whether mutual amusement or, more often, mild but equally satisfying feigned annoyance).

Dad jokes are meant to be obvious and accessible. They are not inside jokes but are open and welcoming. They are, by definition, harmless. They are not mean spirited. They don't make fun of anyone else and are are self-effacing only in that they are deliberately silly.

DAD JOKES.
